# ─── Code Signing Environment Variables ─────────────────────────────────────
# Copy this file to .env.signing and fill in your values.
# .env.signing is gitignored – never commit real credentials.
#
# Run a signed build with:   scripts\build-signed.ps1
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# ── Option A: PFX file (standard OV / EV certificate from any CA) ────────────
# Path to your .pfx certificate file (absolute path).
CSC_LINK=C:\path\to\your-certificate.pfx

# Password that protects the .pfx file.
CSC_KEY_PASSWORD=your-pfx-password


# ── Option B: Windows Certificate Store ──────────────────────────────────────
# Use this instead of Option A when your cert lives in the Windows cert store
# (e.g. EV hardware USB token, or Azure Trusted Signing).
# Set to the "Issued To" / CN field shown in certmgr.msc.
WIN_CSC_SUBJECT_NAME=Your Company Name


# ─── Where to get a certificate ──────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Recommended for indie developers (cheapest → full trust):
#
#  1. Azure Trusted Signing  – ~$10/mo, Microsoft-issued, fastest SmartScreen
#     https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/products/trusted-signing
#     Setup: install AzureSignTool, use WIN_CSC_SUBJECT_NAME
#
#  2. Certum OV certificate  – ~$80/yr, OV = builds SmartScreen reputation
#     https://shop.certum.eu/data-safety/code-signing-certificates.html
#     Use Option A (PFX export from their portal)
#
#  3. DigiCert / Sectigo OV  – ~$200/yr, widely recognised
#
#  4. Any EV certificate      – ~$300–500/yr, instant SmartScreen trust, no warning
#
# After getting a cert, export it as a .pfx (PKCS#12) from your browser or
# the CA portal, then set CSC_LINK + CSC_KEY_PASSWORD above.
